column7: Always write the agenda on the board! Students appreciate seeing the session plan on the board, as it helps them know how the session is structured and what to expect. It also seemed like there wasn’t much collaboration, since everyone was on their own laptops coding. I know coding can make group work challenging, but I suggest trying activities on the board or having students work together on the same laptop could help encourage more collaboration. You could also project code on the board and have the students work from there.

column6: SIL did a great job, especially considering this was her first session. She started with the opener “connections,” where students paired up and found six things they had in common. This was a strong choice because it helped students feel comfortable and created a welcoming environment. I love how you did a warm-up of dimensional problems to ease the students into the content.
column7:
One area for improvement is building more personal connections with students. In the first few minutes before the session begins, try chatting with them about their week or weekend. This helps students feel welcomed and encourages them to come back. Also, don’t be afraid to project your voice more and show confidence. Speaking with more energy and confidence will also make the session feel even more engaging!

For the dimensional analysis warm-up, students weren’t collaborating much. To increase interaction, you might try a “think-pair-share” activity with partners or write parts (a, b, c, d) on the whiteboard and have students come up to solve them. This way, students will be more engaged and talking through the problems together. You could also assign each student one problem, and then have them explain how they did it to the group.

column6:
Right off the bat, I really enjoyed that the session felt welcoming. One of the first things I heard Emma say was "SI is the place to make mistakes!" I always said this in sessions because it's true - SI absolutely is the place to make mistakes (better in session than on an exam) and I'm really glad she's telling the students that. On one of SIL's problems, there was a small mistake and the students pointed it out - I'm not sure if this mistake was intentional or not, but regardless it was a great way to check for understanding, and to make sure that the students are keeping up. 

SIL also checked for understanding using the thumbs method, which is great. She also really did well with redirection questions, asking the students to explain how they worked through the problem and encouraging them to redo old problems in order to practice this topic. Already encouraging students off the bat to go back to previous SI material as a form of review is GREAT! As I left the session, SIL handed out notes organizer worksheets to the students and instructed them to collaborate with the people at their table when completing it.
column7:
When I stepped into the room, the students and Emma were in the middle of doing a problem on the board together. The majority of the students were engaged and had their notebooks out, but a few students in the back table were a little distracted and had their cameras out (photo majors lol) and were kind of messing around. Audrey did a good job at correcting their behavior and making sure they were paying attention, but in general, the students' attention should be fully focused on their SI leaders. 

Emma also looked a little nervous (which is totally understandable bc the inverse square law is hard to do in sessions), but just remember that YOU are the one who has taken the class already, not the students!! You passed the class and know the material, so don't be afraid to own up to that! Even if you're nervous, fake it til you make it - the more confident you are in the material, the better your students will feel too, because they are learning from you. Also I'm nitpicking but don't be afraid to be a little louder!! I know you are a quiet person but the sessions are gonna get busy soon so don't be afraid to take charge :)
column8: no agenda on board but they always put it in their slides lol

column6:
Right off the bat when I came in, SIL and the student were working through a problem together at the board. When they reviewed it together, SIL mentioned to the student that he should always show his work, because the work that he had just done might not have gotten the student full credit for the problem. Immediately following this, the student began working on a second problem and SIL stood back to let the student try the problem on their own. The student ended up doing the problem correctly, worth full points if it were on an exam. They celebrated afterwards! I really loved seeing this interaction between SIL and his student. I can tell that even though there was only one student present at the session, they had great rapport and the student is willing to commit to learning. 

Additionally, SIL did well with facilitation techniques. He was strong in all three, but most especially in redirection questions. A second student showed up about 1/3 of the way through the session, and Julio effortlessly caught the student up to speed and encouraged him to jump in to collaborate with the other student, who was working on a graph. SIL did a great job letting the students take the lead to work on the graphs.

column6: SIL's students were working on IVT and graphing when I walked into the session. Something I immediately noticed about Sofia when I walked in was that she was letting her students collaborate on the problem and giving them limited instruction. One student was up at the whiteboard writing and the second student was close behind, looking at his notes and chiming in with little help from SIL. After they finished the problem, SIL asked them to repeat the steps back to her, which is great checking for understanding. Sofia was very attentive to both her students throughout the session, especially when they were asking questions, and she overall created a welcoming session environment! If I were taking calc, I would love to come to her sessions.
column7: Being pretty nitpicky because the part of your session that I observed was overall really strong - the one thing I did notice is when you were talking to the students about exponential functions, you asked them "does this make sense?" when showing them that negative exponents go on the bottom. Because "does this make sense?" is a simple yes or no question, it gives your students the opportunity to say yes even if they don't fully understand. In the future, you can continue to ask "does this make sense," but follow it up with a deeper question such as "how does this make sense?" or "can you explain why this makes sense?" I hope this is helpful feedback for you!

column6: When I walked into the session, both of SIL's students were collaborating up at the whiteboard solving a problem. SIL was standing back and letting the students work their way through the problem. The students were using each other as a resource and asking each other questions, which was great to see. The students were fully engaged throughout the 15 minutes I was there. One thing I also liked that SIL did is that he knew what format the professor wanted for answers to problems. He made sure his students were aware of the way the professor wants the answers to be written, and I'm sure this will be helpful for when the students have a quiz or test.
column7:
I didn't see an agenda on the board - make sure to include this in case you have students who walk into your session late. I enjoyed how much collaboration there was between your students when they were solving the problems, but I did not see you check for understanding at all when you moved from one problem to the next. Checking for understanding is super important because it ensures that your students are solid on one topic before moving onto the next one. Here are a few different ways you can check for understanding in future sessions:
- thumbs method: have students hold up thumbs up, thumbs in middle, or thumbs down based on how confident they're feeling in the material
- scale of 1 to 5: similar to thumbs, but with numbers. Just ask your students how they are feeling about the material; 1 is bad and 5 is good, etc
- have students repeat the steps of the problem back to you after solving it; this one might work pretty well since you support calc!

column6:
The SI Leader ensured the student was the one doing the writing on the board and only took part in the activity when the student had some questions. He gave some notes on how to improve answers and asked questions to help the student find where they made mistakes instead of just giving the answers themselves. Activities ranged from practice problems (draw the graphs) to discussions (with questions related to specific topics). This is a great way to show the students the range of ways they can study.
He also checked for understanding by asking "why" or "what" questions during the discussion to make sure they completely understood the topic and to hint to solutions during when the student asked him questions.
column7: Make sure to put the agenda on the board. When students are unsure about something, in addition to asking redirecting questions, the SI Leader could also ask them to look at their notes. This will make sure the SI Leader isn't giving too many hints and allows the student to connect the dots themselves.

column6:
The SI Leader tried to make sure the students sat all together so they can collaborate well. The students seemed very comfortable in speaking and collaborating. She did not force the students to speak which made them more comfortable. She also let the students know about the bonus session which is a very good way to market.
She asked them to pull out their notes and asked a lot of redirecting questions during the mind-map activity. She made good use of wait-time at times after asking redirecting questions.
column7:
When doing a mind-map activity, she was drawing and writing out the information on the board herself. It would be more collaborative if the students were the ones at the board drawing everything out and discussing so they could also use active learning to remember the content themselves. When time started to run out, there was more lecturing instead of allowing the students the discuss and figure things out. Instead, she could either adapt her activities to give this one more time or if another activity will be focusing on the same topics later, cut the activity short. 
She could also try to get the students to sit at the tables in the front so they are closer to each other and the board. The students in the back were less engaged in the activity.

column6:
I really liked how the SI used all aspects of the class. Whiteboards were used for student interaction, the class was set up for groups, and the screens were used to display the content to the students. 

Used wait time when the students were confused. In particular, I liked how the SI would redirect the question back to the groups for them to discuss and see if they could figure out the question first. When the students did get the answer, check for understanding was applied by asking the students to explain their reasoning, and a follow-up question was provided. 

Students felt comfortable asking questions and interacting with each other. 

Promoted future sessions and had reminders when everything was finished. 

To really highlight something, I really liked the use of groups, as it helped promote a friendly atmosphere and gave the students more time to talk about and understand the material instead of just answering questions.
column7:
Maybe walk around a bit more to get a feel for how students are feeling while they are actually discussing the questions. It was a little hard to gauge how individual students felt about a question. That group discussion time is a great time to interact with your students and understand where they are at that moment. Especially with a session that size, getting to speak with the students more individually can be important. 

There wasn't too much checking for understanding on the Kahoot questions due to time. Perhaps in the future, the SI might want to keep a closer eye on time during the content portion.

column6:
She did a great job making sure the session was student-led even. The SIL sat down with the group and had them explain concepts while she wrote them down which gave them the time to explain what they knew. She also asked lots of additional/redirecting questions to ensure they really understood the material. 
Also, she did a great job of first asking the students questions to get them speaking and then shifting problem-solving to the students so they were the only ones speaking. This ensured both were both comfortable with speaking up and that they were working together to solve the problem. There was a great use of wait-time as she left the group to continue discussion when it looked like they were struggling to come to a decision on how to proceed with the problem.
column7: She spent the first 7 minutes of session waiting for more students to come. It's fine to give the students some time so they can do collaborative work, but you could also give that time to the opener since you had that planned. That way, the student would have been occupied while others still had some time to come and join.

column6:
You did a great job keeping the students engaged with the activity and trying their best to solve the problems. When the students were struggling, you gave good hints. 
The activity where the students had to work together to put together the solution was a great way to have the students collaborate and check their understanding on the method on how to solve the problem.
You also asked some really good questions to thoroughly check their understanding of the material throughout the session.
column7:
To make the session seem more like a study group, you could have the students working together on the problems or checking each other's answers before you check it. This would allow them to correct each other, explain their reasoning (which would check their understanding), and show them how to study collaboratively. 
When you do collaborative work, ensure both students are participating as a group in solving the problem. Also, it might help them work better together if you don't answer their questions for a few minutes or immediately tell them whether each step is correct. They will then have to rely on each other or their notes if they have an issue which will help them also learn/remember things better.

column6: You did a great job in checking for understanding by having them run through the function and code it themselves. It's also a great idea to have them all code individually but still sit as a group to ensure they can ask each other questions or discuss if needed. You gave them some time and space to work on their own (great use of wait-time) before answering their questions or jumping in. Also, you asked great redirecting questions to students when they asked you a question instead of just giving them the solution. Using a timer was also a great way to make sure you're keeping track of the time you're giving for each activity.
column7:
There were times after you jumped in where a student would say they couldn't understand something or something wasn't working in your code, and you immediately jumped in to help. To promote collaboration, you could instead remind the students to help each other or look over each other's code. This will both help the confused student understand and the others to deepen their understanding by explaining the solution and reading someone else's code. 
Also, you could make the activity itself much more collaborative by having them work in pairs. It allows them to discuss the problem with someone else and learn how to study collaboratively even if someone with the solution isn't present.

column10:
Aaron has been using punch cards to win rubber ducks as marketing for his sessions. He said that his Sunday sessions usually bring in a higher attendance number of students. He walked me through his session plan and I really liked his activities! My favorite one that he explained to me was an activity where he would split students in pairs to work on code problems together (word frequency counter). Aaron said that the content in this activity was similar to what was in the students' labs so he tried to market that to get students to come. After the students work on the problems, each group gives a short presentation about their problem and how they did it, which is a great way to check for understanding.

Aaron said that his relationship with the professor is okay; I recommended reaching out to him to plug SI more in class to hopefully bring in more students for BOTH sessions despite the class size being small. Overall I think Aaron is doing a great job and I really enjoyed his activities that he shared with me!

column7:
It felt that the practice problems jumped between types/difficulty. The SI could consider structuring example problems progressively, building from simple to complex:

Example sequence:

1. Concrete example (e.g., if f(2) = 4, what is f⁻¹(4)?)

2. General form (e.g., if f(x) = y, what is f⁻¹?)

3. Simple instance of the general form (e.g., f(x) = x², find f⁻¹(x))

(cont...)

5. More complex forms (e.g., f(x) = 1/(x+2), g(x) = 1/x - 2, f = f⁻¹?)

Building problems incrementally allows students to consolidate understanding and handle more complex questions with confidence.

column10:
The session was student-led. Employed various collaborative techniques. Activities allowed students to assess their understanding independently before engaging in group work, which can help students assess where they are and foster a better discussion. Promoted active recall and critical thinking, fostering deeper learning and conceptual understanding.

Something small, but the SI should make sure to have at least 3 content activities planned out. Even if you plan on not having time and skipping it, in the event the class runs quickly, it's always good to have a backup planned.
column11:
Marketing:

Suggested using surveys to gather feedback on why students may or may not be showing up, along with incentives on how to get people to fill out those forms:

Offer incentives (e.g., candy night) if a target percentage of the class participates.

Include questions on exam topics (e.g., “How confident are you on topic X, Y, Z?”) to help SIs plan upcoming sessions.

Ask students to rate SI activities that you've done, which can highlight the value of sessions and help you (it also lets no-showers see what they're missing)

Recommended leveraging the teacher as a marketing tool to encourage student participation and awareness of SI sessions, such as attaching SI ads to graded exams.

column6: You did a great job of bringing the students together to work on the problem. You started with one student at the board and then asked others if they could help them when they struggled which ended with all the students discussing the answer. Then, you also checked for the first student's understanding by asking him to explain the solution in his own words. When asking questions, you did a great job of asking students questions by name so they were all participating. You created a very comfortable environment where everyone willingly participated and the session felt like a study group.
column7: Make sure to put the agenda on the board. There were times when you asked a question and waited a few seconds before giving them the answer. Use more wait time here just to give students a chance to process and try to recall the answer and if they still aren't responding, you could have them check their notes first as well so that they both remember the resource and are reminded to take good notes in class to use again.

column6:
You did a good job of being flexible since only one student was there. You became his partner which ensured he wasn't doing everything alone. However, you didn't dominate discussion or answer all the questions yourself. Instead, you gave him the time to figure things out and give you some answer.
When more students came in, you did a great job of jumping out of a one-on-one session and switching out yourself with the new student so they could continue with the activity. You also walked away from the group so they could work without turning to you with their questions which was a great wait-time technique.
column7:
Make sure to put the agenda on the board.
The part of the session I observed was great so this is more of a nitpick. When the student wasn't sure how to answer a question or made a mistake once or twice, you tended to explain the answer out yourself. It might help to redirect the student to related topics, ask redirecting questions to the answer or mistake, or check their notes before you start explaining the answer.

column6: The brain dump was a great opener as it allowed the students to actively recall the material they would go over while filling in each other's gaps through discussion. When the students asked questions, you did a great job of redirecting them to their notes/slides which will remind them to use that resource.  It was also nice that you gave the students an estimate of how long each topic should take since it gives them a better idea of how the session is going and where they're at. You incorporated lots of different kinds of activities and learning styles in your session plan. At the end of the brain dump, asking the redirecting questions was a great way to ensure they understood the topic.
column7: When you ask questions, sometimes use their names to direct the question towards one person so every student is answering/participating. During the "guess the output" activity, if you want to ensure the students collaborate, use strategies like having them alternate who has the marker or have one person write and the other person dictate. If they work independently, have them check each other's answers before you do.

You also demonstrated excellent time management by keeping the session on track and finishing right on time.
column7: One thing to work on is redirecting questions back to the student instead of explaining them yourself. Try to keep the student holding the marker and leading the problem-solving as much as possible. Also, instead of asking if something “makes sense,” have them walk you through the steps to check understanding. You could also add a fun closer to wrap up the session!

Your session felt very comfortable, and the atmosphere was warm and welcoming. You also used wait time effectively, giving students the space to think and respond on their own.
column7: Make sure to write the agenda on the board and get there a little earlier to set up, if possible (you might have a class before). You could also encourage students to sit in the front two rows or group up at tables to make collaboration easier. In addition, instead of having one student at the board at a time, try having everyone come up and work on the problem together or split them into pairs for more interaction.
column8: The SI Leader got here at 12:57pm for her 1pm session and took her a bit of time to set up. Just mentioning here in case it's a recurring problem!

The session felt very natural and the student didn't seem intimidated or awkward with the session, which is great.
column7: A few times you asked questions that started with "Do..." rather than "what do..." or "show me...". The student took their time and responded after thinking about it despite these being yes/no questions. Reframing questions can make the student elaborate more if the student doesn't take as much time to think about it as this student did.

column6: She did a good job of ensuring that the student that came in late came up to the board and was included in the activity. She did a great job redirecting questions. She also had good wait time and drew visuals to help guide the students. She let the students lead the activity and some review and let them check each other's work. Did a great job of having the students write more on the board than she did.
column7: She could work on making sure that everyone in attendance is involved in the activity. There were 2 students that were really engaged with the activity and the SI model, however, there was the student that came in late who spent most of their time at a desk on their computer (this was after an effort was made by Nervana to get them to come to the board, which worked, but they immediately went back to the desk afterwards). She did make multiple efforts to get them to come up to the board and asked if they were doing ok, (which eventually did work after 10 min) She did a great job of not derailing her session to get them to participate. If the 2 students who were doing the activity were mostly talking to each other, she went to check on the student and ask them to participate. Once the student was up at the board, she could have asked more questions and given them a marker to get them involved.

column6:
The Notes Organization activity was a great way to have the students reflect on the material. During the activity, the students were seated in groups and working together which allowed them to compile their knowledge and understanding of the material while still actively recalling things themselves. Having the groups work on each other's notes was a great way to expand their understanding by reading things they might've missed without needing a group discussion where students might not feel comfortable speaking up. The SIL also did a great job by walking around to check on how students were doing without hovering over them and allowing them time to independently work (good use of wait time).
After the students finished writing in their groups, the SIL brought them all back together as a group and had each student explain the things they wrote along with a "thumb-up" check for the other students to check for their understanding. She also asked additional questions to check if they understood other parts of the topic. The activity itself was an amazing way to have the students review and compile their notes which is a great study technique (both individually and in groups).
column7: There wasn't anything I could see during the activity which was worth noting.

She had a great opener (this or that) with fun ones, but then ended with a chemistry based one that allowed her to check for understanding/gauge where the students are at (in terms of knowing the topic). This led perfectly into the first activity! Very smooth transition! Did a great job checking for understanding by having them explain aloud to the group, prompting the students for more information!
